@Dr Jonesey actually, just saying, there's only a vocal minority that's on Heard's side. Most people, men and women included, are on Depp's side. Cause most people are normal enough to realize that abuse happens both ways. 

Also, Depp losing his role of Jack Sparrow and Grindelwald is kind of mixed for me. I do agree with everyone else that it's unfair and just plain sexist, because he didn't do anything wrong. 

But on the other hand, the roles that he lost are those that were in movie franchises that were just getting worse and worse. I'll dive into it:
POTC was pretty good and the first movie was fuckiny iconic. The first two sequels (Dead Man's Chest and At World's End), while not being as good as the first one, were still decent movies that added to the world of the first film and built a genuine story arc that was interesting to watch, even if the first two sequels were unnessesarily long at points. It was when we got to the fourth film (On Stranger Tides) that the franchise officially became dull and just not as fun. The story wasn't that interesting, the shtick was getting old, etc. And then we have Dead Men Tell No Tales, the worst of the franchise so far. On Stranger Tides wasn't good, but at least it was entertaining in areas. It felt big and epic at certain points. DMTNT was just a ripoff of the first film with none of the charm or excitement. It was also around the time where Depp's drug use got worse, and you could tell in the performance with how he slurs every one of his sentences. A lot of people didn't like the film and just thought the franchise should end. 

The Wizarding World is a similar case. The Harry Potter films weren't all that great and they did leave some parts of the books out, but they were still decent adaptations of the source material. Then we got to Fantastic Beasts, a planned pentology of films that just ARE NOT NEEDED and are incredibly lazy and dragged out. It's clear that JK Rowling is just grasping for straws here. The first film was just boring. None of the characters are interesting. The action is a mess. And it was so unnessesarily complicated that it was just a pain to sit through. Crimes of Grindelwald, at least in my opinion, was a slight improvement, with it being easier to follow and having some more memorable imagery. But it was still pretty boring and just dull.  The best parts of the film were Jude Law as Dumbledore and JD as Grindelwald. But even then, when you think about it, they're just ripoffs of Charles Xavier and Magneto from Xmen. "I want to rule/get rid of humans because they're oppressing our group of people, and my old friend thinks they can live in peace together". It's the same concept but with wizards replacing mutants. The film just isn't interesting and the twists have no impact because you don't care about any of the characters.

So yeah, both POTC and the WW franchises are basically in ruin, and even when JD was IN those franchises people were hating them. So, at least to me, JD being gone from those roles is a blessing in disguise. People hated DMTNT and Crimes of Grindelwald even though JD was in them. Whether JD would still be in the roles or not, people would still dislike what the future of these film franchises would offer. I think that this is a chance for JD to do the roles that made people love him in the first place, the ones that are new, real, and dramatic. I heard Minamata and Waiting for the Barbarians were fucking good movies. So, just saying, maybe JD dodged a bullet. Margot Robbie and Mads Mikklesen think that JD being gone from those roles was amazing for their careers, but wait and see what happens.
